ðŸ”¤ What is a String in Python?
In Python, a string is a sequence of characters used to represent text.

You can create a string by putting text inside:

single quotes '...'

double quotes "..."

triple quotes '''...''' or """...""" (used for multi-line strings)

ðŸŽ¯ Key Features of Strings
|----------------------------------------------- |
|Feature	  |  Description                       |
|----------------------------------------------  |
|Immutable  |	Cannot be changed after creation   |
|Indexable	| Each character has an index        | 
|Iterable	  |  Can loop over each character      | 
|------------------------------------------------|


ðŸ”§ Useful String Methods
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
|Method	          |    Description	                     |         Example                           |
|.upper()	        | Converts to uppercase  	             |   "hello".upper() â†’ "HELLO"               |
|.lower()	        | Converts to lowercase	               |   "Hi".lower() â†’ "hi"                     |
|.strip()	        | Removes spaces from start & end	     |   " hi ".strip() â†’ "hi"                   |
|.replace(a, b)	  | Replaces a with b	                   |    "cat".replace("c", "b") â†’ "bat"        |
|.split()	        | Splits string into a list	           |   "a,b,c".split(",") â†’ ['a','b','c']      |
|.find()	          | Finds the index of a substring	     |   "hello".find("l") â†’ 2                 |
|.len() (function) |	Returns the length of the string	   |    len("hello") â†’ 5                     |
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
